But now, Noel and Fairfield are the biggest known losers in the scandal, facing potential losses of $ 7.5 billion, more than half its assets.
At the end of 2007, Optimal had 6 billion euros, or $ 8 billion, under management, according to the bank's annual report- which would mean that its Madoff investments were a substantial part of Optimal's portfolio.
The tally of reported losses climbed through the weekend to nearly $ 20 billion, with a giant Spanish bank, Banco Santander, reporting Sunday that clients of one of its Swiss subsidiaries have lost $ 3 billion.
